A shift for the External Kitchen entails overseeing and monitoring the outdoor kitchen area ( located just outside of the Main Lodge to the right) to make sure that:

  • the propane tanks have been turned off while not in use.
  • the dish washing bins have clean water.
  • The food prep areas are generally clean for all to use.
  • The common utensils have all been cleaned and returned to the proper bin.

Sometimes this means tag teaming with your shift-mates with someone always being on site; sometimes it may mean just periodically checking in.

Most everyone who uses the External Kitchen understands the importance of cleaning up after themselves so the person after them is not left with a mess. All the rules or 'Laws of the land' will be posted on a sign at the entry. As a volunteer, your main goal is to ensure that anyone who uses the External Kitchen has a pleasant experience, that the wash bins are clean and being rotated, and that no one burns the place down.

That's about it... Thanks in advance for signing up.

We will assist to fix or come up with a reasonable solution in a timely manner for most problems that fall within the range of our abilities. Qualifications: Must have general knowledge of tools and the way they work, including knowing if you have the right tool and skill-level for the job, or if you need to find additional resources.

All Karma Patrol volunteers need to be confirmed with the coordinator in advance, a previous email was sent in June to request volunteers for shifts. If you missed this email, please contact at karmapatrolfnf@gmail.com to pick up one of the few times remaining below or to be put on the wait list in case someone cannot make their shift.

Karma Patrol's mission is "Safety in Service." It's all about being a loving, caring, and responsible crew that will patrol the grounds and help those who are in need of support.

During the campout, we will be available to assist those who might be experiencing an uncomfortable situation. This includes medical, dehydration, or chemical issues, as well as any discord that may come up between campers. In addition, we can be counted on us to help protect the property and offer guidance about how to respect the grounds, the staff, and the rest of the FnF community. We are all here for the same reasonâ€¦to have a good time. Karma Patrol aims to maintain the atmosphere of fun by minimizing the things that might get in the way. Karma Patrol is there to be friends and family. Especially if people are having a tough time.

The details: Each KP shift has a 2-person team who will walk around Saratoga Springs for 2 hours with backpacks containing items to help folks in need (basic first aid, water, electrolytes, basic convenience items), a radio to get additional assistance from Site Coordinators or Medical, and an unlimited supply of *consensual* hugs, handshakes, and smiley hellos. When reporting for your shift at the campout, please meet on the porch of the Heart Lodge near the "Karma Patrol" sign and wait for the previous team to arrive to receive hand-off from them. Don the super rad sparkly hot pink Karma Patrol vest and/or your KP t-shirt, the backpack, and your radio. Then hit the dirt to check on the party! At the end of your shift, youâ€™ll return to the Heart Lodge where youâ€™ll hand off to the oncoming shift and give them a short report on anything that may need follow up. There will be a journal to write notes so if anything significant happens, we can track it for resolution. There will be a map with the camping spots of the coordinator and those who are professionally trained to handle psychiatric issues. There will also be a list of sober campers who are available to support others who live substance-free lifestyles. Obviously, these helpful people wonâ€™t be available all the time, but please feel free to use them as resources if they're available. Remember, If things feel too big for you to deal with on your own, donâ€™t hesitate to call a Site Coordinator or Medical. If ever additional assistance is needed from the KP coordinator, please notify the SC on-duty who can reach Cari Lee.

A mandatory orientation will happen at the campout on Friday at 5:30 PM and on Saturday at 11:00 AM. Check your email for more details from the coordinator re: attendance after you've signed up for a shift.

Lastly, Karma Patrol has a "Scope of Practice" document that needs to be read and understood by all volunteers. Check it out here!

} protected job "Karma Patrol" needs 2 repeats starting Friday noon until Sunday 2:00pm for 2 hours

MOLD is the Ministry Of Little Details. We provide campers with small, and hopefully delightful, surprises to make your campout just a little more special (many of these are items you may have planned to bring, but somehow forgot as you rushed out the door or never thought you needed, but would be delighted to find at precisely the right place and time). We need a small staff of energetic and detail oriented helpers to help with setup, replenish supplies, and help us collect and pack what remains at the end of the weekend. Duties of MOLD volunteers may involve the careful placement and restocking of MOLD items, as well as light tidying of the domains of MOLD (bathroom sinks, picnic tables, smoking areas, etc.), and turning-on the mood-lighting in the outhouses. Volunteers will receive a email detailing the specifics of their role prior to the campout.

We are adding a new shift of (Cigarette) Butt Fairy this year. The Butt Fairy is responsible for scooping cigarette butts into the trash from the numerous ash buckets provided around the facility (smoking gazebo, the dance floor & pool gravel pit) as needed throughout the shift - hopefully giving each smoking area a clean start. This helps us meet our target of zero butts on the ground at all times. We prefer to fill this slot with smokers, for obvious reasons.

Meet at the Main Lodge - check-in at the back of ground floor bathroom

There are two types of volunteers we need, senior medics and first responders - don't let either of the titles scare or deter you! But please note that both of these positions require you to be sober. We need reliable, responsible folks for these kinds of possibly difficult situations. Think of it as a good down time to rehydrate yourself.

As a senior medic, you will be the resource for the first responders. Senior medic shifts are four hour-long roving positions, so they carry a radio and are not confined to the medical table for immediate needs, but will offer relief/breaks to the first responder when needed. Ideally we would like those who sign up for senior medic be those folks who are more than just first aid trained. Nurses, doctors, emergency responders and/or those people trained to handle emergency response and challenging situations that the first responders might not be able to manage on their own. Of course though, this isn't a requirement; if you are badass at handling tough situations and donâ€™t freak out under pressure, then please volunteer for the senior medic position. Please email Ajay, or Andrea with your information and intro/reintro, especially if you are taking a Senior Medic slot.

First responders volunteer for two hour shifts and work the medical table/booth that is located on the porch of the Heart Lodge. First responders shifts are staffed as one person with the senior medic available by radio. Even though the first responder is solo at the medical table, rest assured a whole host of people will be hanging out and keeping you company on the porch.

Meet: Medical table, porch of the heart lodge. Friday night at 7pm we will be having a medical team meeting to go over everything. Before then you will receive an email from me (ajay) with additional information.

Meet at the main lodge

Chill Lounge Coordinators: Adrianna, Ahsan and Laura

Chill Room Sound and Lighting: Jason and Jonathan
Chill lounge setup:

2) Sunday Pack up fluff

Heavy lifting required

Heavy lifting required

Picking up after your favorite Friends and Family. Walk-throughs, spot cleaning, and consolidation of trash bags to be placed in the proper dumpsters. Easy cheesy!

Saturday and Sunday we will spend approximately an hour walking the grounds, picking up trash and bagging what is in the trash cans.

Monday will be consolidating trash bags and helping move them to the dumpster at the front gate. We will also spend as much time as necessary bringing SS to better than before we arrived condition.

Meet: On the porch of the Heart Lodge a few minutes before your shift starts.

A shift for the External Kitchen entails overseeing and monitoring the outdoor kitchen area ( located just outside of the Main Lodge to the right) to make sure that:

  • the propane tanks have been turned off while not in use.
  • the dish washing bins have clean water.
  • The food prep areas are generally clean for all to use.
  • The common utensils have all been cleaned and returned to the proper bin.

Sometimes this means tag teaming with your shift-mates with someone always being on site; sometimes it may mean just periodically checking in.

Most everyone who uses the External Kitchen understands the importance of cleaning up after themselves so the person after them is not left with a mess. All the rules or 'Laws of the land' will be posted on a sign at the entry. As a volunteer, your main goal is to ensure that anyone who uses the External Kitchen has a pleasant experience, that the wash bins are clean and being rotated, and that no one burns the place down.

That's about it... Thanks in advance for signing up.

Meet: At the external kitchen!

As FART we are here to help fix and repair small to medium sized issues with your gear or vehicles. We will assist to fix or come up with a reasonable solution in a timely manner for most problems that fall within the range of our abilities. We are here to fix mechanical and worldly things such as your onesie costume, your dead car battery or that tentpole that decided to let go. Sometimes it looks like us helping you fix your own problem, or us showing you how to fix your own problem. Weâ€™ll do our best to lend a hand.

Find our radio beside the MOLD station and med tent, radio the FARTer on Duty and write your issue in the binder and either wait there for us to go back to wherever you need the assistance.

Qualifications: Must have general knowledge of tools and the way they work, including knowing if you have the right tool and skill-level for the job, or if you need to find additional resources.

Details: Meet at the Heart Lodge Patio to start your shift.

Be a part of feeding your Friends and Family at the campout.

Meet in the kitchen 10 minutes before your shift starts. Wear closed toed shoes and have the ability to handle sharp things and hot things without injury to yourself or others.

Gate shift volunteers will greet arriving attendees and:

  1. Direct them in signing the Liability Waiver for FnF
  2. Distribute Tickets
  3. Relay key information about house rules (Leave No Trace, smoking, etc)
The shifts last 1.5 hours and will overlap with a partner. Gate is fun, you get to meet each person arriving and help to set the vibe of the whole event, but it's also a very busy role and its smooth operation is absolutely vital to the party. To help ensure that smooth operation, please show up a few minutes early for your shift.

Meet: at the gate.

Water is provided by Saratoga Springs in pre-bottled 5-gallon jugs. You will deliver full and empty water jugs to all designated locations using a golf cart. During your four hour shift, the two-person hydration team checks to ensure that all hydration stations are sufficiently stocked. These four-hour shifts are fun and you are not always on duty -- you are not working continuously for the full four hours! Fuckin'YAY!

There will be a short training on Friday afternoon and Saturday mid-morning -- further information will be sent out closer to the event for everyone who volunteers.

IMPORTANT: These are VERY important shifts and we need VERY reliable people to fill them -- the the last few years at Saratoga Springs have been very hot. If someone doesn't show up for their shift or follow the instructions many, many people are left without water.

Please do not sign up for one of these shifts unless you are 100% committed to filling it. Thank you!

All Karma Patrol volunteers need to be confirmed with the coordinator in advance, a previous email was sent in June to request volunteers for shifts. If you missed this email, please contact at karmapatrolfnf@gmail.com to pick up one of the few times remaining below or to be put on the wait list in case someone cannot make their shift.

Karma Patrol's mission is "Safety in Service." It's all about being a loving, caring, and responsible crew that will patrol the grounds and help those who are in need of support.

During the campout, we will be available to assist those who might be experiencing an uncomfortable situation. This includes medical, dehydration, or chemical issues, as well as any discord that may come up between campers. In addition, we can be counted on us to help protect the property and offer guidance about how to respect the grounds, the staff, and the rest of the FnF community. We are all here for the same reasonâ€¦to have a good time. Karma Patrol aims to maintain the atmosphere of fun by minimizing the things that might get in the way. Karma Patrol is there to be friends and family. Especially if people are having a tough time.

The details: Each KP shift has a 2-person team who will walk around Saratoga Springs for 2 hours with backpacks containing items to help folks in need (basic first aid, water, electrolytes, basic convenience items), a radio to get additional assistance from Site Coordinators or Medical, and an unlimited supply of *consensual* hugs, handshakes, and smiley hellos. When reporting for your shift at the campout, please meet on the porch of the Heart Lodge near the "Karma Patrol" sign and wait for the previous team to arrive to receive hand-off from them. Don the super rad sparkly hot pink Karma Patrol vest and/or your KP t-shirt, the backpack, and your radio. Then hit the dirt to check on the party! At the end of your shift, youâ€™ll return to the Heart Lodge where youâ€™ll hand off to the oncoming shift and give them a short report on anything that may need follow up. There will be a journal to write notes so if anything significant happens, we can track it for resolution. There will be a map with the camping spots of the coordinator and those who are professionally trained to handle psychiatric issues. There will also be a list of sober campers who are available to support others who live substance-free lifestyles. Obviously, these helpful people wonâ€™t be available all the time, but please feel free to use them as resources if they're available. Remember, If things feel too big for you to deal with on your own, donâ€™t hesitate to call a Site Coordinator or Medical. If ever additional assistance is needed from the KP coordinator, please notify the SC on-duty who can reach Cari Lee.

A mandatory orientation will happen at the campout on Friday at 5:30 PM and on Saturday at 11:00 AM. Check your email for more details from the coordinator re: attendance after you've signed up for a shift.

Lastly, Karma Patrol has a "Scope of Practice" document that needs to be read and understood by all volunteers. Check it out here!

Attendants
Calling all holistic health evangelists and alternative health geeks! We're looking for knowledgeable and enthusiastic attendants to help guests select from our offerings of natural remedies, assist with the healing service appointments, and share information about the workshops scheduled.
Workshop Heralds
In costume of choice, the workshop heralds parade through the campground announcing upcoming Body and Soul Nourishment workshops with that's right....a fantastic sign! If you always wanted to work a sign like you own it, then this is the shift for you! Entice and inspire party goers to follow you back to where the workshops will be led. Feel free to turn it into a parade...the more the merrier! Since herald shifts are short, we ask that you please sign up for multiple shifts.

All attendants and heralds meet at the pop-up MILDEW station outside the pool area.

Ministry of Lost and Found (MILF) helps you find your forgotten stuff. MILF needs help organizing lost items.

Meet on the porch of the Heart Lodge Monday at 12 noon o'clock!

Volunteer page for projects that only need a few volunteers

Clothing Swap Volunteer: Instruct the people who bring clothes to put them on hangers and to hang them up in an orderly and appealing fashion.
Meet at poolside patio
Contact: Flo

Misters and Mistesses - ask yourself, what can possibly be more fun than cooling off your Friends and Family when it is a million degrees outside? Doing it as part of the MIST Team!!! We need some hearty volunteers to wander the party in the heat of the day and provide cool, refreshing MIST!

Meet at the Mist Oasis, in front of the Main Lodge to pick up and drop off the hand misters.

MOLD is the Ministry Of Little Details. We provide campers with small, and hopefully delightful, surprises to make your campout just a little more special (many of these are items you may have planned to bring, but somehow forgot as you rushed out the door or never thought you needed, but would be delighted to find at precisely the right place and time). We need a small staff of energetic and detail oriented helpers to help with setup, replenish supplies, and help us collect and pack what remains at the end of the weekend. Duties of MOLD volunteers may involve the careful placement and restocking of MOLD items, as well as light tidying of the domains of MOLD (bathroom sinks, picnic tables, smoking areas, etc.), and turning-on the mood-lighting in the outhouses. Volunteers will receive a email detailing the specifics of their role prior to the campout.

We are adding a new shift of (Cigarette) Butt Fairy this year. The Butt Fairy is responsible for scooping cigarette butts into the trash from the numerous ash buckets provided around the facility (smoking gazebo, the dance floor & pool gravel pit) as needed throughout the shift - hopefully giving each smoking area a clean start. This helps us meet our target of zero butts on the ground at all times. We prefer to fill this slot with smokers, for obvious reasons.

Meet at the Main Lodge - check-in at the back of ground floor bathroom

There are two types of volunteers we need, senior medics and first responders - don't let either of the titles scare or deter you! But please note that both of these positions require you to be sober. We need reliable, responsible folks for these kinds of possibly difficult situations. Think of it as a good down time to rehydrate yourself.

As a senior medic, you will be the resource for the first responders. Senior medic shifts are four hour-long roving positions, so they carry a radio and are not confined to the medical table for immediate needs, but will offer relief/breaks to the first responder when needed. Ideally we would like those who sign up for senior medic be those folks who are more than just first aid trained. Nurses, doctors, emergency responders and/or those people trained to handle emergency response and challenging situations that the first responders might not be able to manage on their own. Of course though, this isn't a requirement; if you are badass at handling tough situations and donâ€™t freak out under pressure, then please volunteer for the senior medic position. Please email Ajay, or Andrea with your information and intro/reintro, especially if you are taking a Senior Medic slot.

First responders volunteer for two hour shifts and work the medical table/booth that is located on the porch of the Heart Lodge. First responders shifts are staffed as one person with the senior medic available by radio. Even though the first responder is solo at the medical table, rest assured a whole host of people will be hanging out and keeping you company on the porch.

Meet: Medical table, porch of the heart lodge. Friday night at 7pm we will be having a medical team meeting to go over everything. Before then you will receive an email from me (ajay) with additional information.

Park cars. Follow the parking lot filling plan as closely as practical (it will be provided). Improvise wisely and conservatively. Appear to be sober. Keep the cooler in shade. And yes, park cars â€“ its kinda important.
